            {
               "text": "### Images from El Salvador Museo\n\nThese images are copyright for El Salvador Museo and allowed to be used according to the license determined by them.\n\nTo visualize all images, use the left and right arrows on the slide below.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htSlides\"><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">1 / 2</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgBering\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgBering', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">A map showing Indigenous migration routes across the Bering Strait. Photo taken at the Museo Nacional de Antropología en San Salvador, El Salvador (<htcite0>), on <htdate0>.</div><div class=\"htSlideRefs\"><b>Related content:</b><ul><li>Who truly discovered America (<i>Abya Yala</i>)? (Who... ?)</li></ul></div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">2 / 2</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"img1\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img1', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Babylonian world map © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite1>) superimposed on the modern world map © Mapswire (<htcite2>). Shariing under <a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0)</a> license.</div><div class=\"htSlideRefs\"><b>Related content:</b><ul><li>Atlas: America: Inca (Tawantinsuyu) - Location of the Inca Empire on the American continent. (<htcite3>)</li><li>Atlas: America: Mesoamerica (Different Frontiers) - We study a broader proposal for the limits of Mesoamerica. (<htcite4>)</li><li>Atlas: America: Mesoamerica (The Beginning) - We study the first proposal for a region called Mesoamerica. (<htcite5>)</li><li>Atlas: America: Minas Gerais (BR) - Location of the state of Minas Gerais, Brazil, in the world. (<htcite6>)</li><li>Atlas: Bantu Expansion - Explanation of the Bantu expansion across Sub-Saharan Africa. (<htcite7>)</li><li>Atlas: Comparing Worlds - Comparison between the world understood by the Babylonians and our current world. (<htcite8>)</li><li>Atlas: Continent: Africa - Location of the African continent on the planet. (<htcite9>)</li><li>Atlas: Continent: Antarctica - Location of the Antarctic continent on the planet. (<htcite10>)</li><li>Atlas: Continent: Asia - Location of the Asian continent in the world. (<htcite11>)</li><li>Atlas: Continent: Europe - Geographic location of Europe. (<htcite12>)</li><li>Atlas: Continent: Oceania - Location of the continent of Oceania on the globe. (<htcite13>)</li><li>Atlas: Cradle of Civilization - There are several civilizational cradles, which is why we dedicate a text to introducing them. (<htcite14>)</li><li>Atlas: Europe: Banu Qasi - Region of dominion of the Banu Qasi on the Iberian Peninsula. (<htcite15>)</li><li>Atlas: Europe: Kingdom of León - Map of the Kingdom of León on the Iberian Peninsula. (<htcite16>)</li><li>Atlas: Europe: Visigoths - Map of the Visigoths on the Iberian Peninsula. (<htcite17>)</li><li>Atlas: Great Zimbabwe - civilization built by the Shona people, one of the Bantu-speaking groups, in Zimbabwe. (<htcite18>)</li><li>Atlas: Human Migration - We study human migration across planet Earth. (<htcite19>)</li><li>Atlas: Our Coordinates - Explanation about the planet's geographic coordinates. (<htcite20>)</li><li>Atlas: Subcontinent: North America - Location of North America in the world. (<htcite21>)</li><li>Atlas: Subcontinent: South America - Location of the South American subcontinent in the world. (<htcite22>)</li><li>Atlas: Sumerians - Geographic presentation of where the Sumerian peoples were located. (<htcite23>)</li><li>Atlas: Surface Coordinates - We study what surface coordinates are. (<htcite24>)</li><li>Atlas: The Ancient Babylonian World Map - Babylon: Study of the first known world map. (<htcite25>)</li><li>Atlas: The Size of the Earth - Text describing the first measurements of the planet's size. (<htcite26>)</li><li>Atlas: Where are we on a sphere? - How we locate ourselves on a sphere. (<htcite27>)</li><li>Atlas: Where is the center? - We explain the different centers of the planet from the perspective of different peoples. (<htcite28>)</li><li>First Steps (Volume 1): Our Week - Can We Group the Year Into Weeks? In this text, we explore the calculations made by the Amorites and by ourselves. (<htcite29>)</li><li>First Steps (Volume 1): Understanding the Multiplication Tables (Summary) - After studying 10 multiplication tables, we will review the content. But now, we will follow the opposite direction, starting with charts until we reach the general formula. (<htcite30>)</li><li>First Steps (Volume 2): Modulating (Part I) - In this text, we learn that walking in an opposite direction has many things in common with walking in a direction we are used to. (<htcite31>)</li><li>First Steps (Volume 2): Modulating (Part II) - In this text, we present the concept of a 'negative multiplication table' and how it can help us understand the other side. (<htcite32>)</li><li>First Steps (Volume 2): Modulating (Part III) - Continuing from the previous text, we see how the 'negative multiplication table' allows us to deepen our understanding of inclinations. (<htcite33>)</li><li>History: Chronology - Is it possible to create a universal timeline applicable to all of humanity? (<htcite34>)</li><li>History: Cradles of civilization (Part I) - While humanity originated in Africa, the first civilizations emerged in various regions around the world, such as Mesopotamia, the Andes, and Mesoamerica. (<htcite35>)</li><li>History: Cradles of civilization (Parte II) - We continue our study by exploring the civilizations of Egypt, Indus Valley, and China. (<htcite36>)</li><li>History: Culture and Civilization - Is there a hierarchy between them? (<htcite37>)</li><li>Understanding Texts: Anachronism - although it is a word unknown to many, it is an action frequently practiced. (<htcite38>)</li><li>Understanding Texts: Equality Levels - Some concepts, like the definition of a planet, change over time. Sometimes, objects with slightly different sizes can be considered equal. How can we use numbers to quantify equality? (<htcite39>)</li><li>Understanding Texts: Fractionating Texts - In this text, we delve deeper into the concept of groups and introduce fractions as an additional tool for understanding texts. (<htcite40>)</li><li>Understanding Texts: The Writing System - More than just a tool for daily use, the writing system is a milestone that allows us to divide human history into prehistory and recorded events. (<htcite41>)</li><li>Mathematical Games: Yupana (Multiplication) - Using the same method (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('a62b520a-f443-4d83-ab51-b99c9a46dab8'); return false;\">Prem, Dhavit</a>), multiplication is also presented visually. (<htcite42>)</li><li>Myths and Believes: Did texts written in Mesopotamia describe the world we know today? - To properly answer this question, it is necessary to understand what was meant by 'world' in ancient times. Since the first known world map did not even mention nearby regions, it is not possible to claim that they had any idea of the true size of the world when they referred to their 'known world'. (<htcite43>)</li><li>Myths and Believes: Did the Indigenous peoples lack the knowledge and technology to build pyramids? - The Indigenous civilizations of the Americas (<i>Abya Yala</i>) had all the knowledge necessary to construct monumental buildings on the continent. This was mainly due to careful observation of nature. Regarding the mathematical tools they used, they also left direct and indirect evidence that they mastered them. (<htcite44>)</li><li>Myths and Believes: Has there never been a flood? - There have been several; after all, for a flood to occur, it is enough for torrential rains to cause major disasters. (<htcite45>)</li><li>Physics: Expanding... - Continuing from the previous text, we see that dividing into just two sides ends up doing omissions (<htcite46>)</li></ul></div></div><i class=\"fa-solid fa-chevron-left htSlidePrev\" onclick=\"htPlusDivs(-1);\"></i><i class=\"fa-solid fa-chevron-right htSlideNext\" onclick=\"htPlusDivs(1);\"></i></div></p>",
